<DOC><DOCNO> AP880602-0035 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0649EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-02 0516</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,510</SECOND><HEAD>DC, Baltimore Mayors Back National Debate on DrugDecriminalization</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The mayors of the nation's capital and nearbyBaltimore have renewed their call for a national debate on thedecriminalization of illegal drugs, with Baltimore's chiefexecutive saying that cutting out profits is the key to shuttingdown drug dealers.   ``As you look at our so-called war (on drugs), we're losing,''said District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr. during a livetelevision call-in show Wednesday night.   ``I think there ought to be a full debate on what our optionsare,'' said Barry.   ``I'm not calling for a retreat on the war on drugs,'' saidBaltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke, who touched off a firestorm of debateseveral weeks ago when he first suggested the possibility ofdecriminalization. ``I want to fight on the battlefield of the drugdealers _ money.''   Schmoke also said that Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who chairsthe House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, hasagreed to hold hearings on the decriminalization issue, probably inSeptember.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Congress Urged To Regulate Test-Tube Baby Industry</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One member of Congress is urging thegovernment to take an active role in protecting would-be parentswho seek help in having children from the nation's test-tube babyindustry.   ``Frustrated couples, many at an emotional breaking point,shouldn't also have to face those who would exploit their faith inmodern medicine,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. at a hearingWednesday.   Wyden, chairman of the House Small Business subcommittee onregulation and business opportunities, cited a recent congressionalstudy that found more than half of the 169 clinics in the UnitedStates performing in-vitro fertilization (IVF) last year neverproduced a baby. A woman's chance of taking home a test-tube babyis about 6 percent he said.   The study for the congressional Office of Technology Assessmentalso showed Americans spent $1 billion last year to combatinfertility.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Judge Strikes Down Ban On Secrecy Pledges</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge says the Reagan administrationcan require government workers to sign secrecy pledges.   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch, in a May 27 ruling made publicthis week, struck down a congressional provision that would havebarred the administration's action taken during the first 10 monthsof this year.   Gasch said the provision contained in a spending resolutionpassed by Congress last December unconstitutionally intruded on thepresident's power to protect government secrets.   ``With a tug of the purse strings section 630 (of the spendingresolution) establishes a precedent unrestrained by discerniblestandards and intrudes dramatically upon presidential authority,''Gasch said.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Average Public School Salaries Reported in Survey</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The average public school teacher makes about$28,000 annually, according to a recent survey by an educationresearch group.   The annual survey, conducted by the Educational ResearchService, found average salaries this year ranged from $28,230 forteachers to $68,147 for superintendents.   The salary data, reported in last month's issue of ``Principal''magazine, was gathered in a survey of teachers and administratorsin 1,000 public school districts.</TEXT></DOC>